elements.title: Swiss fishing industry
elements.contents: ... that perch became a major product of the Swiss fishing industry (fishing boat pictured) in the mid–20th century after a fisherman found that an industrial potato peeler made two perfect filets from each fish?

elements.title: Andantino
elements.contents: ... that Jerome Robbins choreographed the ballet Andantino to music by Tchaikovsky, despite his lack of interest, because "you don't necessarily have to enjoy doing something for it to be good"?

elements.title: Jameela Al Salman
elements.contents: ... that infectious diseases specialist Jameela Al Salman has supported the development of medical robots and called their use in Bahrain a "pioneering experiment"?

elements.title: Queen of Rhodesia
elements.contents: ... that despite being proclaimed Queen of Rhodesia, Elizabeth II refused to recognise the title?

elements.title: Princess Lucia
elements.contents: ... that Princess Lucia was so unpopular ruling in the name of her teenage son Bohemond that he sought permission from the pope to come of age early?

elements.title: Everywhere at the End of Time
elements.contents: ... that the album series Everywhere at the End of Time (2016–2019) by the Caretaker uses ballroom records to depict the stages of Alzheimer's disease?

elements.title: George M'Kinley
elements.contents: ... that Royal Navy officer George M'Kinley was blinded during a gun drill?

elements.title: Pomona College
elements.contents: ... that students at Pomona College are traditionally thrown into a fountain on their birthday?
